comments.text:
It's the same thing why people play the card game Solitaire, rearrange virtual gems or pieces of candy on their smart phones or why some folks enjoy managing their inventory or their entire base in any given rpg and/or survival game ... the progress from chaos to order holds immense satisfaction. Couple that with clear visual feedback and a sense of mastery, break down large tasks into smaller manageable chunks, and there you have it. Plus it gets you into this kind of flow state, where you zone out and forget all your real life problems. I mean, don't get me wrong, I still prefer slaying dragons in Skyrim or go hunting for some radioactive artifacts ins Stalker, but I still can pretty much understand why so many people enjoy these kind of games.

Anyway, enough said. Great video by the way! After watching one of your videos about ChatGPT and now stumbling across this one, you just got yourself a new subscriber. So, yeah, keep up the great work! 👍

After learning about these types of games, especially after seeing Code Monkey review Retail Simulator, I considered trying to make one.  I decided against it because I just can't relate to wanting to play that kind of game, and so might not be able to make a good game of a type I don't understand.  
When I think of a "simulation game," I think of top-down management/god games like those of the 90s (which is how I think of The Sims as well, managing a household, while seeing Stardew Valley as an RPG).
